INSERT INTO `skeleton_item_richtext` (`item_richtext_nodeID`, `item_richtext_data`) VALUES
(405, '<p>A <b>pixel</b> is the smallest element of detail in a digital image.</p><p>A pixel is also the smallest division of a flat panel (LCD or plasma) display capable of making up part of an image.</p><h2><b>Origin</b></h2><p>The term pixel is said to originate from the words â€˜picture elementâ€™, where â€˜pixâ€™ is an informal name for â€˜picturesâ€™.</p><h2><b>Technical information</b></h2><p>Modern televisions and computers are capable of displaying images\r\nand videos from digital sources such as digital television (terrestrial\r\nor cable), DVDs, blu-ray discs, computer hard drives, and more.</p><p>In order for an image, including a frame from a video, to be\r\ncaptured, stored or displayed digitally, the image must be broken down\r\ninto a discrete number of separate, measurable numeric values.&nbsp; This is\r\nbecause digital media cannot store an image as a continuous surface,\r\nbut must break it up into discrete parts that can be stored as numeric\r\ndata.</p><p>Digital images have therefore been divided horizontally and\r\nvertically into thousands of small elements called pixels.&nbsp; Each pixel\r\nis treated by the digital system as a single numeric value, or in the\r\ncase of color images, as up to three values representing three color\r\nchannels.</p><p>A digital image cannot contain any detail smaller than a single\r\npixel.&nbsp; The number of pixels that comprise a digital image, therefore,\r\ndictates the level of fine detail that can be present in the image.</p><p>The density of pixels on a given surface is known as the <i>resolution</i>.&nbsp; A resolution of 300dpi means that there are 300 rows of columns of pixels along a length of an inch.</p><p>In video, the term resolution is also used to refer to the dimension\r\nof the image in pixels.&nbsp;&nbsp; For example, an image with dimensions of\r\n1024Ã—768 pixels consists of 1024 columns of pixels, in 768 rows.&nbsp;\r\nIncidentally, from these dimensions we can find that there are 786,432\r\ntotal pixels in the image (1024 x 768).</p><p>Various different media have different resolutions.</p><ul><li>The picture on a video DVD usually has a resolution of 720Ã—480\r\npixels in North America and Japan, and 720Ã—576 pixels in all other\r\nplaces.&nbsp; However, these pictures are interlaced: Every successive\r\npicture contains only the odd or even rows of pixels.</li><li>The picture on a blu-ray disc usually has a resolution of 1920Ã—1080\r\npixels.&nbsp; This is the same in all countries.&nbsp; This picture is not\r\ninterlaced, which means that every successive picture contains all of\r\nthe pixels of the image.</li><li>A high definition television picture can consist of a variety of\r\nresolutions ranging from 720Ã—480 pixels to 1920Ã—1080 pixels, though\r\nmany people do not consider it to be proper high definition if it is\r\nnot at least 720 pixels in height.</li></ul><p>Analog mediums such as analog video, VHS videotapes and film do not\r\nstore images digitally and the concept of a pixel does not apply.&nbsp;\r\nAnalog video and VHS videotapes store picture as a continuous analog\r\nsignal scanning from left to right over an image, over a certain number\r\nof rows.&nbsp; Therefore analog video is made up of â€˜linesâ€™ and does indeed\r\nhave an inherent vertical resolution, but not horizontal as the\r\nhorizontal signal is continuous.&nbsp; A picture on film is continuous in\r\nboth dimensions and has no concept of resolution.</p><h2><b>Points of confusion</b></h2><p>Some people may quote a given horizontal resolution for an analog\r\npicture.&nbsp; This resolution is usually a statistic used to give an idea\r\nof the amount of detail present in the continuous analog signal.&nbsp; The\r\nresolution does not relate to any actual pixels but instead to the\r\ntheoretical smallest amount of detail that could be reproduced.</p><p>Flat panel screens including LCD and plasma display screens display\r\nimages digitally.&nbsp; However, these screens have their own resolution,\r\ntermed <i>native resolution</i>.&nbsp; Often, the native resolution of the\r\nscreen wonâ€™t match the resolution of the incoming digital picture.&nbsp; For\r\nexample, a digital picture from a blu-ray disc player contains\r\n1920Ã—1080 pixels.&nbsp; However, many LCD screens will have a native\r\nresolution of 1365Ã—768 pixels.&nbsp; In this case, the screen will\r\nautomatically downscale the incoming image, reducing the overall number\r\nof pixels.&nbsp; This is a mathematical calculation, and involves combining\r\ninformation from multiple pixels in the source image into a single\r\npixel in the new image.&nbsp; Some detail is lost as a result.&nbsp; When you are\r\nchoosing a flat panel screen you should therefore pay attention to its\r\nnative resolution, making sure it is high enough to reproduce the\r\npicture you intend to play without downscaling.</p><p>If a flat panel display such as an LCD of plasma display has a fault\r\nin a single pixel, it is often referred to as a â€˜dead pixelâ€™.&nbsp; A dead\r\npixel will never light up, and if the surrounding pixels are lit it\r\nwill appear as a permanent black dot on the screen.&nbsp; A â€˜hot pixelâ€™, by\r\ncontrast, is always lit.&nbsp; A hot pixel will display as a permanent\r\ncolored dot on the screen whenever it is turned on, even when the rest\r\nof the screen has gone dark.&nbsp; Rarely, an entire row or column of pixels\r\nmay be â€˜deadâ€™ or â€˜hotâ€™ creating a black or colored line, and indicating\r\na much more serious problem with the panel.&nbsp; If the panel is under\r\nwarranty, you should try to get it replaced.&nbsp; However, some\r\nmanufacturers and retailers do not consider a single dead pixel as\r\nenough of a defect to warrant a replacement.&nbsp; If you would be annoyed\r\nby a permanent black or colored dot, check the policy of your retailer\r\nand manufacturer with regard to dead or hot pixels before purchasing.</p>');
