(431, '<p>Any software application which encourages\r\nor requires you to pass on messages to your friends is a bad thing.&nbsp;\r\nFacebook is a culprit because it promotes applications which do this.</p><p>Applications that do this are a bad thing because while the person\r\nusing the application is not inconvenienced very much, it will annoy\r\nall that personâ€™s friends.&nbsp; They, unfortunately, had no say in whether\r\nthey got this piece of advertising sent to them.&nbsp; Because it came to\r\nthem via a friend - someone they know - they feel they canâ€™t complain.</p><p>Itâ€™s something that is pissing me off about <a href="http://www.facebook.com/">Facebook</a> at the moment, but before I go to that I wanted to talk about about viral marketing.</p><p>Although based on a pre-existing concept, the buzzword <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viral_marketing">viral marketing</a>\r\ncomes from pre-2.0 web days, and refers to any marketing which is done\r\nby encouraging people to pass a marketing message on to their friends,\r\nvoluntarily.</p><p>The idea that this is voluntary is key here.&nbsp; Sure, perhaps none of\r\nthe â€˜friendsâ€™ solicited this advertising, but the idea is that the\r\nperson passing on the message truly wants to spread the good word about\r\na product or service.&nbsp; Letâ€™s say I eat a delicious meal of fish and\r\nchips.&nbsp; If I recommend it to a couple of my friends, I am participating\r\nin viral marketing.&nbsp; In order to put this into motion, the fish and\r\nchip shop had to create a product that was so compelling, its customers\r\ncould not help but to spread the good word to their friends.</p><p>The problem worsens slightly when the passing on of such marketing\r\nmessages is not entirely voluntary: it is influenced in some way. For\r\nexample, a web application will suggest that the user forward something\r\nto their friends, making it easy to do so by providing a special form\r\njust for this purpose. This makes the passing on of the message less of\r\na natural, evolutionary process where the best products will generate\r\nthe most interest, and transforms it into a process where companies\r\noffer various gimmicks to encourage people to â€˜forwardâ€™ messages to\r\ntheir friends.&nbsp; The messages just start to get annoying.</p><p>Iâ€™m annoyed when I see that I have a message (email, SMS or some\r\nother online message) from a friend, only to open it and find out it\r\nis, well, spam.&nbsp; Iâ€™m even more annoyed to suspect Iâ€™m not the only one\r\nwho received the message: that my friend probably spammed a whole bunch\r\nof people, and I am only one of many.&nbsp; Itâ€™s a small slap in the face to\r\nfind that a message from a friend is not a personal message at all but\r\nwas forwarded.&nbsp; Itâ€™s a much larger slap in the face when itâ€™s an\r\nobvious commercial or hoax message with little to no hint of\r\npersonalisation from the friend - no â€˜hey M. I thought youâ€™d be\r\ninterested in this cos you like horror moviesâ€™, just the impersonal\r\nforwarded message.</p><p>This is what the term viral marketing came to mean on the web.&nbsp;\r\nClaiming on the surface to be a natural, non-intrusive process in which\r\npeople only pass on messages to friends who they believe will genuinely\r\nand personally benefit, itâ€™s grown into a group of industries that seek\r\nto exploit people by preying on their gullibility and the carelessness\r\nwith which they will send on messages to their friends for a trivial\r\nreward.</p><p>Marketing is not the only motivation behind getting people to\r\nforward messages on to their friends.&nbsp; Some people or companies do it\r\njust to get a kick out of seeing how far their message spreads.&nbsp; This\r\nis the case with hoaxes and chain letters, both of which deceive people\r\nin order to get them to forward the message on to their friends.&nbsp; The\r\nlatter lie about various benefits the user will receive if they forward\r\nthe message.&nbsp; These can prey on the superstitious (â€™forward this to 20\r\npeople or your hair will fall outâ€™), the greedy (â€™send a $1 to this\r\nperson and before long youâ€™ll receive over $300â€²) or otherwise gullible\r\n(â€™forward this message to all your friends so that Microsoft donâ€™t shut\r\ndown your accountâ€™).</p><p>Email itself can be a problem.&nbsp; The relative ease with which\r\nsomebody could forward a received message to their entire address book\r\nused to land countless chain letters in my inbox, though people seem to\r\nbe a lot more educated about the problems of spam these days that it\r\nisnâ€™t so much a problem - besides, there are far greater problems with\r\nemail spam.</p><p>Facebook is a bad thing because it allows for applications to be\r\nbuilt which require or encourage you to pass on messages to your\r\nfriends. It is too easy for applications to exploit users into passing\r\nmessages around the network, because every Facebook user is inherently\r\nconnected with a network of friends, including friends who share trust,\r\nand are interested in communicating with each other.&nbsp; Facebook users\r\ninstall applications which are written by third parties, with varying\r\nmotivations for creating them. In many cases it appears that the\r\napplication developer simply wanted to get a kick out of seeing how\r\nquickly their application would travel around the network.&nbsp;\r\nApplications also derive income from advertising, which ties the\r\ndeveloperâ€™s bottom line to the number of people using the application.</p><p>Some of the fastest spreading Facebook applications are the most\r\nannoying. For example, the applications â€˜Super Wallâ€™, â€˜Fun Wallâ€™, any\r\napplication which appears to be some sort of IQ or personality test\r\n(with the exception of the one actually called â€˜IQ Testâ€™), â€˜Top\r\nFriendsâ€™ and more have spread quickly through the network due in part\r\nto the fact that in order to participate in them, your friends have to\r\nbe involved too.&nbsp; However, these applications exploit people as\r\ndescribed below.</p><p>â€˜Super Wallâ€™ and â€˜Fun Wallâ€™ lead users to believe that only by\r\ninstalling this application will they be able to send and receive wall\r\nposts containing videos, pictures or gifts, but these are all available\r\nin the regular built-in wall.&nbsp; The only unique feature of these\r\napplications is the existence of a â€˜Forwardâ€™ button below every post,\r\nwhich makes it easy for users to forward a message to not just one, but\r\nmany of their friends at once.&nbsp; The messages sent through these\r\napplications are therefore much less likely to be personal, as they are\r\nused to send messages at large to many people.&nbsp; This has given birth to\r\nthe phrase â€˜click forward see what happensâ€™, a gullibility test in\r\nitself which has failed enough people that hoax messages like these\r\nlitter the entire network, proving to be an annoyance to everyone, not\r\nonly those that fell for the lie.</p><p>A number of times have I installed an application that seems like a\r\nrelatively fun and silly test - of my personality, for example - and\r\nhave filled out the entire questionnaire only to find that in order to\r\nsee any results I have to forward an advertisement to at least 20 of my\r\nfriends. Presumably, the fact that I invested so much time filling out\r\nwhat I thought was just an amusing little test will outweigh the guilt\r\nof annoying a bunch of my friends with a promotional message\r\nencouraging them to install a certain application, and Iâ€™ll go ahead\r\nand spam them in order to get my results.&nbsp; Not me though.&nbsp; I will\r\nsimply get angry and give up on seeing the results, concluding that I\r\nhave just had ten or twenty minutes of my free time wasted in the name\r\nof trying to get me to spam my friends.</p><p>Perhaps if Facebook were not such a ubiquitous and otherwise useful\r\nmedium I wouldnâ€™t be nearly as annoyed.&nbsp; I have received invitations to\r\ndo various things in other social networking software and have just\r\nturned it down, because it didnâ€™t seem worth using them anyway.&nbsp; But\r\nnearly everyone I know my age has a Facebook account - I can only think\r\nof two friends my age who donâ€™t. Itâ€™s becoming such a normal way to\r\ncommunicate with people.&nbsp; Some friends even send out invitations to\r\nsocial events through it.</p><p>I guess that Facebook could remove the ability for applications to\r\nforward messages to many people at once.&nbsp; But the entire network stands\r\nto benefit so much from the rapid take-up of its applications that I\r\npresume theyâ€™d be resistant to taking steps to limit this spread.</p><p>I maintain, however, that applications, such as Facebook\r\napplications, which encourage or require users to pass on messages to\r\nfriends are a bad thing and should somehow be restricted.&nbsp; There is no\r\nneed to remove the ability for someone to tell a friend about an\r\napplication altogether.&nbsp; But it shouldnâ€™t be allowed to be forced or\r\nencouraged, for if this is done it ceases to promote adoption of\r\napplications based on their true merit and becomes a competition in\r\nwhich application developers try to deceive or exploit people.</p><p><b>Further reading</b></p><ul><li><a href="http://www.latimes.com/technology/la-ca-webscout27jan27,1,46127.story?track=rss&amp;ctrack=1&amp;cset=true">So sorry - didnâ€™t mean to spam you</a> David Sarno, Los Angeles Times 7 Jan 2008, Los Angeles<br />\r\nâ€˜Facebook users, angry at being turned into junk-mail senders, prompt a change.â€™</li><li><a href="http://www.digitalministry.com.au/component/option,com_myblog/Itemid,142/show,445/">On Facebook, nobody knows your dog is spam</a> Alan Jones, Digital Ministry 16 Jan 2008, Australia</li><li><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/bigyahu/2192019848/">Dog Facebook spam</a> â€˜thatjonesboyâ€™, Flickr.com user, 14 Jan 2008, Sydney<br />\r\nNote: authorship of this piece of text is unclear since the same text appears in <a href="http://www.google.com.au/search?q=%22Somehow,+the+psychology+of+Facebook+convinced%22&amp;num=100&amp;hl=en&amp;safe=off&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;hs=le7&amp;filter=0">a number of locations</a>.</li></ul>'),
(429, '<p><b>CRT</b> stands for <b>Cathode Ray Tube</b>, a screen technology used in televisions and other displays for over 80 years.</p><p>Picture is produced on a surface at the front of a glass vacuum tube.&nbsp; CRT displays are not <i>flat panel displays</i> and therefore take up more space.</p><h2><b>Benefits</b></h2><p>As CRT is a much older technology compared to LCD and plasma display\r\npanels, a high quality CRT screen can be much cheaper than a low-range\r\nLCD or plasma screen.</p><p>CRT does not exhibit the limited viewing angle or response time delay of LCD panels.</p><p>CRT displays do not have a <i>native resolution</i> like flat panel\r\ndisplays do.&nbsp; If they are capable of displaying high definition picture\r\nat all, they will display it without any downscaling.</p><p>CRT is known to have excellent color and contrast reproduction, though LCD panels are fast catching up.</p><h2><b>Drawbacks</b></h2><p>CRT displays are very heavy and take up a lot of space when compared\r\nto flat panel technologies like LCD and plasma display panels.</p><p>CRT displays may deteriorate with age, producing less sharp or more unstable picture.</p><p>Magnets, or devices which contain magnets or produce a magnetic\r\nfield, should never be placed too close to an operational CRT display\r\nas it may cause distortion, or in some cases permanent damage.&nbsp;\r\nSpeakers are a common culprit because they contain strong magnets.&nbsp;\r\nMake sure any speakers are placed at least a foot away from any part of\r\nthe picture tube unless you are sure that the speakers are <i>magnetically shielded</i>.</p><h2><b>Technical information</b></h2><p>CRT displays consist of a large glass vacuum tube with electron guns\r\nmounted at the rear, and colored phosphors covering a panel at the\r\nfront.&nbsp; The electron guns shoot a beam of charged particles through the\r\nvacuum toward the phosphors at the front.&nbsp; When hitting the phosphors,\r\ncolored light is produced.</p><p>The electron beams are steered left and right over 30,000 times per\r\nsecond, and sweeps from top to bottom either 50 or 60 times per second,\r\ncovering the entire screenâ€™s area 50 or 60 times per second, fast\r\nenough to give humans the illusion that the entire screen is lit at\r\nonce.&nbsp; The beamâ€™s intensity is varied as it scans, allowing an image to\r\nbe formed.</p><p>A shadow mask (or aperture grille) ensures that each beam only hits\r\neither the red, green or blue phosphors on the screen.&nbsp; When lit\r\ntogether, these can reproduce all colors.</p><p>CRT technology can also be used in projectors.&nbsp; When used in\r\nprojectors, the three color guns (red, green and blue) are usually in\r\nthree separate vacuum tubes instead of one, allowing a greater level of\r\nfine detail in smallish tubes.&nbsp; The front of each tube has a large lens\r\nin front of it, focusing the image onto a distant surface like a wall.&nbsp;\r\nCRT projectors require some rather complication <i>calibration</i> to ensure that all three colors line up properly and the picture on each is perfectly in focus.</p><h2><b>Points of confusion</b></h2><p>Some CRT displays are advertised as being <i>flat screen</i>.&nbsp; This\r\nusually means that the front surface of the vacuum tube is flat rather\r\nthan curved, reducing distortion.&nbsp; It is not to be confused with a flat\r\npanel display like LCD or plasma.&nbsp; Sometimes, a CRT display advertised\r\nas being flat screen still has a curved screen, but uses a glass lens\r\nat the front whose outer surface is flat to make the display appear\r\nflat.&nbsp; It is more expensive to produce a CRT display with a true flat\r\nfront surface for structural reasons; the glass tube must withstand the\r\nforce of the vacuum inside.</p><p>CRT displays rarely accept any type of digital video signal such as\r\nDVI or HDMI.&nbsp; They are inherently analogue, and usually perform at\r\ntheir best with a component video connection.</p><h2><b>Recommendation</b></h2><p>CRT displays are dropping in popularity due to the emergence of LCD\r\nand plasma displays.&nbsp; This means it can be hard to find them for sale\r\nanymore, and unfortunately many of those that are still sold cater to\r\nthe budget conscious and arenâ€™t very good screens.&nbsp; If you can find a\r\ngood quality high definition widescreen CRT screen that is not too old,\r\nyou can probably get it at a bargain.&nbsp; Otherwise, go for an LCD, but\r\nkeep in mind youâ€™ll be paying much more for an equivalent screen.</p>'),
(427, '<p><b>Contrast ratio</b>\r\nis a specification usually applied to screens such as television sets,\r\ndescribing the ratio of brightnesses it can display from the brightest\r\nwhites to the darkest blacks.</p><p>A high contrast ratio may result in blacker looking blacks.</p><h2><b>Technical information</b></h2><p>Contrast ratio is expressed as a ratio.&nbsp; A 1000:1 contrast ratio\r\nmeans that under ideal conditions, the blackest parts of an image will\r\ngive off less than one thousandth of the light that the lightest parts\r\nwill.</p><p>Contrast ratio is usually measured in a completely dark room, with\r\nthe screen set to its maximum contrast level.&nbsp; In the case of LCD\r\npanels, the backlight will be boosted to its highest possible\r\nbrightness.&nbsp; The brightness of the light emitted will then be measured\r\nwith the screen showing full white, and again with the screen showing\r\nfull black.</p><p>A low contrast ratio will usually indicate that the black areas of\r\nan image will appear milky gray, rather than black.&nbsp; Any contrast ratio\r\nbelow 300:1 will appear inferior, though will still be watchable.&nbsp; A\r\ncontrast ratio of 1000:1 or better will look great.</p><h2><b>Points of confusion</b></h2><p>Contrast ratios are measured in conditions in which we would not\r\nnormally watch our screens.&nbsp; For example, because the black level is\r\nmeasured with a full black screen in a dark room, it doesnâ€™t indicate\r\nthat the same contrast will be obtained between black and white areas\r\ndisplayed simultaneously, when light from the white part can leak into\r\nthe black part, or reflect off objects in the room.&nbsp; Some panels will\r\noptimize themselves for this synthetic contrast ratio measurement by\r\ndropping the backlight intensity when the screen is showing full\r\nblack.&nbsp; Similarly, we rarely watch television with the contrast and\r\nbacklight settings on their maximum values.&nbsp; Finally, the synthetic\r\ncontrast ratio measurement gives no indication of what the actual\r\ncontrast ratio will be in a room containing ambient light.</p><h2><b>Recommendations</b></h2><p>Donâ€™t attribute too much importance to contrast ratio.&nbsp; While you\r\nshould watch out for anything that claims a really poor contrast ratio\r\nless than 300:1, anything higher than this and the individual\r\ndifferences are more likely going to come down to factors which arenâ€™t\r\nmeasured in the synthetic measurement.&nbsp; Keep in mind that film used in\r\nmovie theatres has a contrast ratio somewhere around 500:1, and\r\ntherefore that ratios higher than this become more and more meaningless\r\nand theoretical.</p>'),
(428, '<p><b>Speakers</b>, or <b>loudspeakers</b>, produce sound.</p><h2><b>Form factors</b></h2><p>Speakers come in many different form factors, for different purposes.</p><ul><li>Floorstanding speakers are full length speakers intended to sit\r\nflush on the floor.&nbsp; They are the tallest speakers available, and are\r\nintended to reproduce a full range of audio frequencies.&nbsp; Unless space\r\nis an issue, floorstanding speakers are recommended as the main front\r\n(left and right) speakers in any hi-fi or home theatre setup.</li><li>Bookshelf speakers are not as tall as floorstanding speakers, and\r\nare intended to be mounted on stands.&nbsp; As is implied by their name,\r\nthey may also be mounted on a shelf.&nbsp; Bookshelf speakers reproduce a\r\ngood range of audio frequencies, though their bass response will not\r\nusually be as good as floorstanding speakers.&nbsp; Bookshelf speakers may\r\nbe used as main front speakers in a small room or where space is an\r\nissue.</li><li>Center speakers are specially designed speakers which are intended\r\nto reproduce a â€˜centerâ€™ audio channel in a home theatre setup.&nbsp; They\r\nare often slim, in order to fit neatly above or below a television\r\nscreen without being too distracting.&nbsp; They are also often magnetically\r\nshielded, so they may be safely placed close to a CRT television, and\r\nare sold in single units rather than in pairs.&nbsp; Center speakers are\r\noften very similar in build to equivalent small bookshelf speakers,\r\nexcept that they are symmetrical when lying down flat instead of\r\nsitting up.&nbsp; They can reproduce at least all mid-range and high\r\nfrequency sounds, while they do not usually produce much, if any, bass.</li><li>Bipole speakers are speakers which spread sound in two separate\r\ndirections, instead of directly toward the listener.&nbsp; This creates a\r\nbetter illusion of sound â€™surroundingâ€™ the listener, as at least part\r\nof the sound heard has been reflected off walls or other objects.&nbsp;\r\nBipole speakers are usually used only as surround or rear speakers, as\r\nthey have been specifically designed for this purpose and would be\r\nquite unsuitable for main speakers.</li><li>Satellite speakers are very small speakers intended as either main\r\nor surround speakers.&nbsp; The speaker unit can be as small as a coffee\r\ncup, or even smaller.&nbsp; They only reproduce a very limited range of\r\nfrequencies and need to be paired with a specially matched woofer, to\r\nbe placed somewhere else in the room.&nbsp; Satellite speakers are not\r\nrecommended in circumstances where audio quality is important; their\r\nform factor exists mainly for looks rather than function.</li><li>A subwoofer is a large speaker designed to sit on the floor and\r\nprovide very deep bass sounds.&nbsp; Sometimes, a subwoofer can contain a\r\nbuilt-in amplifier, requiring it to be plugged in to a power socket.&nbsp;\r\nThis type of subwoofer is called an â€˜activeâ€™ subwoofer.&nbsp; Subwoofers are\r\nnot capable of producing the frequencies heard in speech, and thus\r\ntheir use is normally restricted to special effects in movies.&nbsp; They\r\nmay also help to reproduce some of the low frequencies that the main\r\nfront speakers are not capable of reproducing, especially if they are\r\nbookshelf or satellite speakers.</li><li>Computer speakers are very small speakers intended to sit on a desk\r\nnear a computer monitor, providing sound for a computer.&nbsp; Computer\r\nspeakers are usuallyvery low quality, mounted in plastic.&nbsp; They often\r\ncontain an in-built amplifier, requiring them to be plugged in to a\r\npower socket.</li><li>Headphones are worn on the head, for private listening.</li></ul><h2><b>Technical information</b></h2><p>Almost all speakers consist of one or more drivers.&nbsp; Most drivers\r\nconsist of a cone-shaped diaphragm made of a combination of paper,\r\ncloth and/or a synthetic material.&nbsp; The cone is rigid and can move\r\nforward and backward on its central axis.&nbsp; An electromagnet in the back\r\nof the cone repels and attracts it to and from a large magnet at the\r\nrear of the driver.&nbsp; This causes the cone to move.&nbsp; When the cone moves\r\nforward it compresses the air in front of it, and when it moves back it\r\ndecompresses air.&nbsp; These local pressure changes in the air travel as\r\nsound waves.</p><p>Drivers of different sizes and shapes are best at producing certain\r\nfrequencies of sounds.&nbsp; As a generalisation, the larger a speaker\r\ndriver, the more able it is to produce deeper bass sounds.</p><p>Sound that humans can hear is usually in the range of 20Hz (20\r\nmovements of a speaker cone per second) and 20,000Hz.&nbsp; Most speaker\r\nsystems can reproduce from around 60-80Hz to 20,000Hz without the aid\r\nof a subwoofer.</p><p>Different types of driver are often matched together in the same\r\nenclosure in order to cover a wide range of frequencies.&nbsp; This is the\r\ncase in floorstanding, bookshelf and center speakers.&nbsp; A two-way\r\nspeaker unit contains two different types of drivers, whereas a\r\nthree-way speaker unit contains three different types of drivers.&nbsp; In\r\neach, the drivers used to produce the highest treble sounds are called\r\ntweeters, and the drivers used to produce most lower sounds are called\r\nwoofers.&nbsp; Electronic devices called crossovers are used to separate the\r\nincoming audio into high and low frequencies, or high, mid, and low\r\nfrequencies, for two- and three-way speaker units.</p><h2><b>Points of confusion</b></h2><p>Speaker units have terminals on the back that accept either bare\r\nstranded wire, or banana plugs, or either.&nbsp; Even though it seems to fit\r\neither way, it is important to hook up your speakers using the correct <i>polarity</i>\r\n- that is, the red terminal on the speaker must connect to the red\r\nterminal on the amplifier, and the black (or uncolored) terminal must\r\nconnect to the black terminal on the amplifier.&nbsp; Otherwise, your\r\nspeakers may oppose each other - the high pressure part of a cycle on\r\none might coincide with the low pressure part of a cycle on the other,\r\ncancelling it out and making a â€˜tinnyâ€™ or â€˜lifelessâ€™ sound which varies\r\ngreatly according to where the listener sits.</p><p>Speaker units quote a maximum power level that they may operate at\r\nwithout distortion.&nbsp; This will be measured in Watts RMS (a way of\r\nmeasuring power on an alternating current).&nbsp; This may lead some people\r\nto believe that they should avoid connecting it to an amplifier that\r\nputs out more power than this.&nbsp; To a large extent, the opposite is\r\ntrue.&nbsp; It is best to connect an amplifier capable of matching or\r\nexceeding the speakersâ€™ maximum power handling without distortion, and\r\nlisten at an appropriate volume.&nbsp; The distortion from an underpowered\r\namplifier can cause permanent damage to a speaker even within the\r\nspeakerâ€™s maximum power rating.</p><h2><b>Recommendations</b></h2><p>Your front left and right speakers are the most important in any\r\nsetup, and your front center speaker if you have one.&nbsp; If you cannot\r\nafford a high quality 5 channel speaker setup, it is better to settle\r\nfor two high quality stereo speakers than five low quality home theatre\r\nspeakers.&nbsp; DVDs, blu-ray discs and high definition television which\r\nuses multiple channels will sound very good coming out of just two\r\nspeakers if the speakers are good.</p><p>If you have the space and the money, get floorstanding front\r\nspeakers.&nbsp; If they are good quality you will be very impressed with\r\nthem, especially for movies.</p><p>Avoid satellite speakers.&nbsp; They are sold more for their appearance\r\nthan their sound quality.&nbsp; Their small size made them very fashionable\r\nat a time, but their low frequency cutoff means that voices and music\r\nwill suffer, requiring the accompanying matched â€˜wooferâ€™ to fill in\r\nlower sounds.</p><p>The way you mount your speakers and their location can affect their\r\nsound.&nbsp; Avoid mounting main front or centre speakers within a few feet\r\nfrom the corner of a room, or within a foot or so of a wall.&nbsp; The\r\nlayout of your living room may dictate this somewhat.&nbsp; Avoid mounting\r\nspeakers on top of wooden boards that may cause a rattling sound.&nbsp; You\r\ncan buy special mounting feet (â€™spikesâ€™) at an audio enthusiasts store,\r\nor you could try damping the rattle using, for example, and old\r\nmagazine.</p><p>If you get a subwoofer, be very careful to avoid the temptation of\r\nsetting its level so high that it distorts, or it â€˜boomsâ€™.&nbsp; A subwoofer\r\nshould never be heard on its own - its sound should just blend in with\r\nthe rest of the sound from your system.&nbsp; Experiment with lots of\r\ndifferent locations to see which sounds best.</p>'),
(433, '<p><img src="http://www.randomjabber.com/images/uploads/secrets.jpg" alt="Secrets" title="Secrets" /></p><p>A month ago fellow blogger <a href="http://www.jarkkolaine.com/" title="Jarkko Laine">Jarkko Laine</a> participated in the <a href="http://jarkkolaine.com/2008/01/30/no-more-secrets" title="No More Secrets">no more secrets</a>\r\nmeme and tagged me to do the same. I told Jarkko that I would also\r\nparticipate but as you can see, time got away from me and Iâ€™m about a\r\nmonth late. Better late than never right?</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>Well, without further ado, here are my seven secrets:</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>1. I Hate to Read</h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>Unlike Jarkko, I absolutely hate to read. I donâ€™t mind reading books as a reference (CSS, HTML,\r\netc.) but I cannot read a book from cover to cover, just canâ€™t do it.\r\nMy mind wanders to much. Whenever Iâ€™ve tried to read a book, my mind\r\nalways wanders and it ends with me thinking about a CSS problem, development of my next site or I have an epiphany about my golf swing that I just have to write down before I forget.</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>2. I Cannot Stand People Eating With Their Mouth Open</h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>This\r\nhas been something that has bugged me for a while. I think it all came\r\nabout when I was growing up, my younger sister would always chew with\r\nher mouth open just to annoy me. Now, when Iâ€™m sitting in the vicinity\r\nof someone chewing anything with their mouth open, with every chew itâ€™s\r\nlike nails down the chalkboard to me.</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>3. I Hate My Food to Touch</h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>Again,\r\nI have no idea how this ever came about, but as long as I can remember\r\nIâ€™ve hated for the food on my plate to touch. If my plate didnâ€™t have\r\nthe little dividers, I would take extra care to ensure nothing on the\r\nplate touched; never getting anything like green beans that may have\r\njuice that could make itâ€™s way over to the other items on my plate. I\r\nalso used to eat each item on my plate one at a time, never moving to\r\nthe next item until the first item I started eating first was finished.\r\nI was able to shake this habit though.</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>4. Little Things Bug Me</h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>Most\r\nof the little things Iâ€™m referring too involves the web. When Iâ€™m\r\ndeveloping a website, the tiniest thing could keep me up at night.\r\nThere have been times that I have stayed up for three or four hours\r\nlonger than I anticipate staying up simply because of a couple pixels\r\nbeing out of place. I just hate for things to not work like I want them\r\nand will torture myself until they are fixed. Iâ€™m getting better at\r\nthis, but not there yet.</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>5. Iâ€™m a Perfectionist </h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>I\r\nknow itâ€™s a pretty common thing for people to say that theyâ€™re a\r\nperfectionist, but I really am. I cannot accept mediocrity. If I cannot\r\ndo something well, I would rather not do it at all. This is most\r\nprevalent in my golf game. Statistics show the â€œaverageâ€ golfer will\r\nnormally shoot scores right around the 100 mark. My normal scores are\r\ngenerally in the low to mid 70â€™s (the lower the better). It drives me\r\nabsolutely nuts to play a round of golf and not play to what I consider\r\nâ€œgoodâ€ or â€œaverageâ€ for myself. It bugs me so much so, that after a bad\r\nround, Iâ€™ll spend the next week or so visiting the driving range on my\r\nlunch break as well as after work trying to figure out just what it is\r\nthat Iâ€™m doing wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n	<h2>Iâ€™m Tagging You!</h2>\r\n\r\n	<p>Now\r\nyou know five secrets about me. The rule of the game is that I get to\r\npass the tag on to some bloggers and they get to do the same thing on\r\ntheir sites:</p>\r\n\r\n	<ul><li><a href="http://www.susansuarez.com/" title="Susan Suarez">Susan</a></li><li><a href="http://www.storypixel.com/" title="Sam Wilson">Sam</a></li><li><a href="http://www.davidairey.com/" title="David Airey">David</a></li><li><a href="http://www.stuffbysarah.net/" title="Stuff by Sarah">Sarah</a></li></ul>\r\n\r\n			<p><a href="http://www.randomjabber.com/blog/article/i-was-tagged-to-share-my-secrets/#commentform" title="Permalink to I Was Tagged to Share My Secrets"><br /></a></p>'),
(434, '<p><strong>The number of users browsing the Web from a mobile device continues to rise, yet most mobile web sites are still sub-par.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing is, creating a great web experience for users of mobile\r\ndevices is much easier than you might think. In this article I''ll\r\nintroduce seven fundamental steps that, if followed, will help you\r\navoid the pitfalls that have caused many other mobile sites to fail. By\r\nthe end of this article you''ll know exactly where to focus your efforts\r\nin order to build a successful mobile site.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>1. Don''t Mix Up Your Markup </h5>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>A few different types of markup are available for building a mobile\r\nweb site. You''ll need to choose one that suits the needs of your\r\ncustomers and stick with it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em><a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/glossary.php?q=W#term_69" title="WML, or Wireless Markup Language, is the language used to format content for wireless devices.">WML</a></em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the early days of mobile web devices, the only way to surf the mobile web was to browse <a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/glossary.php?q=W#term_71" title="WAP or wireless area protocol is a protocol that allows the delivery of Web content to mobile phones.">WAP</a>\r\n(Wireless Application Protocol) sites. A WAP site uses WML (Wireless\r\nMarkup Language) as its primary markup language. WML is an <a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/glossary.php?q=X#term_3" title="eXtensible Markup Language, or XML, is a text markup language designed for the easy sharing of data.">XML</a> markup language based on the card-and-deck metaphor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luckily for us, WML has since been superseded by several other\r\ntechnologies -- in fact, if you''re just getting into the mobile web\r\ngame, you can probably ignore WML entirely. WML is mostly used by\r\nlegacy systems or by sites that explicitly target customers with\r\nlow-end phones that are six years old or older.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One potential group of customers still using WML browsers, however, is those in developing nations. The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nokia_3310">Nokia 1100 and 1101</a>,\r\nfor example, are extremely basic, extremely cheap phones, of which an\r\nestimated 200 million units have been solid worldwide, making this\r\nphone the best-selling model to date, worldwide. If your site is\r\ntargeted to this market segment, WML might be the best solution for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em><a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/glossary.php?q=X#term_63" title="XHTML is a reformulation of HTML 4 as an XML 1.0 application.">XHTML</a></em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For most sites, we can ignore WML and make use of a markup language with which you''re probably much more familiar -- XHTML.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most built-in phone browsers these days can handle XHTML just fine. A mobile phone recognizes two flavors of HTML:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol><li>XHTML -- the same, basic XHTML rendered by desktop web browsers</li><li><br /></li><li>XHTML-MP -- the MP here stands for Mobile Profile</li></ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The difference between these two languages is that XHTML-MP consists\r\nof slightly fewer elements and tighter restrictions. These differences\r\nexist to make it easier for the mobile device to parse and render a web\r\ndocument, but writing XHTML-MP markup shouldn''t introduce any\r\nsignificant changes to your process for writing regular XHTML.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anecdotally, when my team and I develop mobile web sites we usually\r\nuse regular XHTML, and this approach has served us just fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>2. Know Your Phones</h5>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>As plasma and HD TVs slowly hit the market, broadcasters have run\r\ninto the problem of where to place their logo and news tickers.\r\nPreviously, they knew that all TVs were the same 3x2 dimensions, so\r\nthey knew the relative width of the screen. Now, they''re beginning to\r\nfeel the pain of dealing with a wide assortment of TV resolutions and\r\ndimensions -- an issue that web developers deal with on a daily basis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, the mobile world is even worse! Not only must we cater\r\nfor different screen sizes and resolutions, but also different shapes,\r\nas Figure 1 illustrates. From rectangles that are short and long, to\r\nthose that are tall and skinny, to perfect squares, the mobile world\r\ncontains a rich tapestry of variation that almost makes you want to\r\npull your hair out!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image001.png"><em>Figure 1. Overlays of major phone dimensions (click to view image)</em><img src="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image001.png" alt="" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you consider the most common phones available, they can be\r\ncategorized on the basis of screen size -- give or take a few pixels:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>128 x 160 pixels</li><li>176 x 220 pixels</li><li>240 x 320 pixels</li><li>320 x 480 pixels</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Knowing these screen dimensions helps you optimize some of your\r\ncontent, however it''s best to keep the shape and style of your site as\r\nminimal and linear as possible. There is no mouse on a mobile phone --\r\nonly an up-down feature -- so you can''t demand that users jump around\r\nthe page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image003.thumb.jpg"><em>Figure 2. Sony Ericsson T630, Nokia 6600, Blackberry 8800, iPhone (click to view image)</em><img src="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image003.thumb.jpg" alt="" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em>iPhone/Internet-tablet versus old green-screen phones</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a couple of exceptions to the norm in the mobile phone\r\nmarket. They are the really high-end devices like the iPhone or the\r\nNokia Internet Tablet, and the very basic, old "green-screen"\r\nmonochrome dot matrix devices such as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nokia_3310">Nokia 3310</a>, both of which are shown in Figure 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image005.jpg"><em>The Nokia N810 High-end Internet Tablet, and the most popular phone in the world â€“ the Nokia 1100 (click to view image)</em><img src="http://i2.sitepoint.com/graphics/1618image005.jpg" alt="" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Low-end mobile phones have several limitations, including screen\r\nresolution and a severely limited ability to render XHTML documents. As\r\nI mentioned in the previous section, if a majority of your customers\r\nfall in this group, then maybe WML is still for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the other end of the spectrum, high-end devices often have the\r\nability to run a web browser that''s comparable to one you might use on\r\na desktop machine. Delivering a quality user experience to these\r\ndevices can be tricky -- while the device may be perfectly capable of\r\nrendering a full, traditional web page design, it''s probably\r\ntransmitting data over a cellular network, which is much slower than\r\nstandard broadband Internet speeds. So even though the device can\r\nhandle a normal web site, the customer''s situation and the reason why\r\nthey''re requesting your services may mean that sending them the normal\r\nversion of your web site isn''t the best solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We''ll see in the next section what this means for the design of your mobile site.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>3. Target the Right Customers</h5>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The goal for any web site should be to know your customers in order to deliver to them the most appropriate content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This goal is even more important with mobile sites -- not only do\r\nyou need to know your customers, but you need to know what they are\r\nlikely to be doing on your mobile site, as well as where they''ll be\r\nwhen they''re doing it. Traditional web site customers are most likely\r\nsitting at a desk facing a large monitor that has a decent resolution.\r\nVisitors who are browsing your mobile site are unlikely to be in the\r\nsame circumstances -- they might be waiting in line, riding on the\r\ntrain or the bus, running to the departure gate, or lost in an\r\nunfamiliar town late at night and trying to get somewhere. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Google is one company that has invested considerable effort into\r\nstreamlining its web applications to suit mobile users. The web\r\ndevelopers at Google have identified and focused on three main groups,\r\nand they attempt to target their applications to those customers''\r\nneeds. These are three solid categories, and are worth examining for\r\nyour own mobile site. Let''s look at them now.</p>'),
(436, '<h2>High priority</h2><ul><li><a href="http://skeleton/install-repair-tool-skeleton">Install/repair tool</a></li><li>Image selector/uploader for WYSIWYG</li><li>Link selector/uploader for WYSIWYG</li><li>Tool for administering user accounts</li></ul><h2>Bug fixes</h2><ul><li>Make sure it isn''t possible within any admin tool to lock everyone out of a node - there should always be at least one person who can both view and admin the node.&nbsp; One way to achieve this would be to make sure you can''t remove any privileges for the ''admin'' group.<br /></li></ul><h2>Low priority</h2><ul><li>Auto-update internal links in content</li><li><ul><li>Some sort of tool that can be used in for example rich text boxes</li><li>Make sure internal links are identified so that a session ID can be added where necessary<br /></li></ul></li></ul>'),
(438, '<h2>Authentication</h2><p>Installer should check authentication at the very start, and then re-affirm authentication on every page load using a session hash.</p><p>If config.inc.php does not exist:</p><ul><li>It should check that a valid MySQL username, password and hostname was supplied.</li></ul><p>If config.inc.php does exist:</p><ul><li>It should try to check that a valid root-node administrator has logged in.</li></ul><p>On a successful login, it should issue a session hash.&nbsp; This hash should depend on the user and IP and time, and a secret code made of the username and password of the logged in user or the username and password for the database.</p><h2>Bootstrapping</h2><p>By this time, we should either have a valid connection to a database server (but not necessarily knowing which database and prefix to use) or a valid connection, chosen database and logged in user.</p><p>If the database and prefix aren''t known yet, give the user some options.</p><ul><li>Go hunting around all visible databases for existing Skeleton installations.&nbsp; List these to the user and allow the user to ''repair this existing installation''.</li><li>Go hunting around for all visible databases which we have CREATE permission in.&nbsp; List these to the user and allow the user to ''start a new installation'' in these databases.</li><li>Check if we have CREATE DATABASE and GRANT permissions in the database server.&nbsp; If so, list this an option under ''start a new installation''.</li></ul><p>The default value should be ''repair this existing installation'' if there are existing ones found.&nbsp; The pre-selected installation can be the one with the ''node'' table having the latest creation date.</p><p>If there are no existing installations found the default and only option will be ''start a new installation''.&nbsp; The pre-selected value should be to create a new database if possible, otherwise it should be the existing writable database with the fewest tables.</p><p>Checking for existing installations should consist of:</p><ul><li>Check for table names ending in ''node'', ''path'', and ''user''.&nbsp; Each installation must have all three of them with the same prefix.</li><li>The ''node'' table must have columns named ''node_ID'', ''node_parentID'' and ''node_title''.</li></ul><h2>Setting up tables</h2><p>Now tables should be set up as done in definetables.inc.php.</p><h2>Check writeable directories</h2><p>These directories should all be writeable.&nbsp; If they aren''t, halt with an error message explaining that they need to be made writeable.&nbsp; Otherwise, move right along, no need to display anything.</p><ul><li>Cache directory</li><li>Data directory</li><li>Templates directory and directory for each style and any ''c'' directories below those.</li></ul><h2>Initialise database</h2><ul><li><a href="http://skeleton/initialise-database-procedure">Initialise database</a></li></ul><h2>Create node sets</h2><p>Always create set of admin nodes</p><p>Optionally create other node sets based on checkboxes ticked by user.&nbsp; Examples may include:</p><ul><li>Privacy policy</li><li>About us page</li><li>Blog</li><li>Sample article categories</li></ul><p>Node sets should have the ability to search for existing page matches based on a wide range of criteria including types of children, proximity to root node and more.&nbsp; They should have the ability to set custom permissions including those for known ''admin'' or ''editor'' groups.</p><h2>Check database consistency</h2><p>Use existing consistencycheck.</p><p>Note: checking nodes and paths not yet complete - will have to implement a way to move recovered nodes to an inactive folder.</p><h2>Clean up</h2><ul><li>Rebuild permission tables</li><li>Rebuild node relationships table</li><li>Re-compile templates</li><li>Wipe data cache</li></ul><h2>Write config.inc.php</h2><p>Based on template in includes/system/configtemplate.tpl.php</p><p>If file isn''t writeable, display on screen in a textarea or similar for copying and pasting.</p>'),
(441, '<h2>Group, user, groupuser, permission and add permission<br /></h2><p>Give the ''everybody'' group view access to the root node, unless there were already any permissions in the permissions table.</p><p>Either the user logs in as a root node admin, or the user didn''t log in (and config.inc.php doesn''t exist).&nbsp; If the user didn''t log in, ask them to supply username, password and email address for themselves and create a user based on this.</p><p>Check that the user has full access to the root node of the application and at least view and admin access everywhere else.&nbsp; If so, continue.&nbsp; If not:</p><ul><li>Check if the user is in an admin usergroup already, to which no other person belongs.&nbsp; If not, create a new admin group specifically for them.<br /></li><li>Grant full access to the root node for the user''s admin group, and eliminate any other permission which would deny them admin or view access anywhere else.</li></ul><p>If there isn''t one with the name already, create a group called ''editors'' and give them all permissions except admin permission throughout the site.</p><p>At root node, grant ''admin'' group (and ''editors'' group if it seems to have the default set of perms) appropriate creation permissions for each type.</p><p>Types should have the ability to suggest add permissions for administrators and editors.&nbsp; Iterate through the installed types and give add permissions for the admin group (and editors group if it was the default or new) at root node.</p><h2>Action, type and trinket<br /></h2><p>\r\nThe installed modules should give values for their entry in the action, items or trinkets table.&nbsp; If\r\nthere is an existing value for an icon and it seems to point to a valid\r\nfile then leave it, otherwise always overwrite with official values from module.</p><h2>Node and path<br /></h2><p>\r\nMake sure there is a root node.&nbsp; If there isn''t, create one, with an appropriate type.</p><p>Make sure that there is a path for the root node and it is valid.&nbsp; If not, create a path.&nbsp; Try to base its URL on the currently used URL.&nbsp; Ask the user if necessary.</p><h2>Useroption</h2><p>Insert standard values into this table.&nbsp; Where they already exist, keep any customised title and description.</p><h2>Nodeoptions</h2><p>Check to ensure that root node has all the recommended nodeoptions.&nbsp; If they aren''t there, set them up, possibly with input from the user for ''site title'', emails, and client URL.&nbsp; Pre-fill client URL based on path.</p><h2>Task</h2><p>Insert standard values into this table, overwriting existing entries.&nbsp; Leave unrecognised entries untouched, except make sure nextrun is sane for all records.</p>');
