(405, 382, 1, 'pixel', 'Pixel', 14, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'A pixel is the smallest element of detail in a digital image. A pixel is also the smallest division of a flat panel (LCD or plasma) display capable of making up part of an image.', 'A pixel is the smallest element of detail in a digital image A pixel is also the smallest division of a flat panel LCD or plasma display capable of making up part of an image Origin The term pixel is said to originate from the words â picture elementâ where â pixâ is an informal name for â picturesâ Technical information Modern televisions and computers are capable of displaying images and videos from digital sources such as digital television terrestrial or cable DVDs blu ray discs computer hard drives and more In order for an image including a frame from a video to be captured stored or displayed digitally the image must be broken down into a discrete number of separate measurable numeric values This is because digital media cannot store an image as a continuous surface but must break it up into discrete parts that can be stored as numeric data Digital images have therefore been divided horizontally and vertically into thousands of small elements called pixels Each pixel is treated by the digital system as a single numeric value or in the case of color images as up to three values representing three color channels A digital image cannot contain any detail smaller than a single pixel The number of pixels that comprise a digital image therefore dictates the level of fine detail that can be present in the image The density of pixels on a given surface is known as the resolution A resolution of 300dpi means that there are 300 rows of columns of pixels along a length of an inch In video the term resolution is also used to refer to the dimension of the image in pixels For example an image with dimensions of 1024Ã 768 pixels consists of 1024 columns of pixels in 768 rows Incidentally from these dimensions we can find that there are 786 432 total pixels in the image 1024 x 768 Various different media have different resolutions The picture on a video DVD usually has a resolution of 720Ã 480 pixels in North America and Japan and 720Ã 576 pixels in all other places However these pictures are interlaced Every successive picture contains only the odd or even rows of pixels The picture on a blu ray disc usually has a resolution of 1920Ã 1080 pixels This is the same in all countries This picture is not interlaced which means that every successive picture contains all of the pixels of the image A high definition television picture can consist of a variety of resolutions ranging from 720Ã 480 pixels to 1920Ã 1080 pixels though many people do not consider it to be proper high definition if it is not at least 720 pixels in height Analog mediums such as analog video VHS videotapes and film do not store images digitally and the concept of a pixel does not apply Analog video and VHS videotapes store picture as a continuous analog signal scanning from left to right over an image over a certain number of rows Therefore analog video is made up of â linesâ and does indeed have an inherent vertical resolution but not horizontal as the horizontal signal is continuous A picture on film is continuous in both dimensions and has no concept of resolution Points of confusion Some people may quote a given horizontal resolution for an analog picture This resolution is usually a statistic used to give an idea of the amount of detail present in the continuous analog signal The resolution does not relate to any actual pixels but instead to the theoretical smallest amount of detail that could be reproduced Flat panel screens including LCD and plasma display screens display images digitally However these screens have their own resolution termed native resolution Often the native resolution of the screen wonâ t match the resolution of the incoming digital picture For example a digital picture from a blu ray disc player contains 1920Ã 1080 pixels However many LCD screens will have a native resolution of 1365Ã 768 pixels In this case the screen will automatically downscale the incoming image reducing the overall number of pixels This is a mathematical calculation and involves combining information from multiple pixels in the source image into a single pixel in the new image Some detail is lost as a result When you are choosing a flat panel screen you should therefore pay attention to its native resolution making sure it is high enough to reproduce the picture you intend to play without downscaling If a flat panel display such as an LCD of plasma display has a fault in a single pixel it is often referred to as a â dead pixelâ A dead pixel will never light up and if the surrounding pixels are lit it will appear as a permanent black dot on the screen A â hot pixelâ by contrast is always lit A hot pixel will display as a permanent colored dot on the screen whenever it is turned on even when the rest of the screen has gone dark Rarely an entire row or column of pixels may be â deadâ or â hotâ creating a black or colored line and indicating a much more serious problem with the panel If the panel is under warranty you should try to get it replaced However some manufacturers and retailers do not consider a single dead pixel as enough of a defect to warrant a replacement If you would be annoyed by a permanent black or colored dot check the policy of your retailer and manufacturer with regard to dead or hot pixels before purchasing', 'pixels,image,pixel,resolution,picture,digital,display,detail,panel,analog', 1107521965, 1206376491, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
