(429, 382, 1, 'crt', 'CRT', 14, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'CRT stands for Cathode Ray Tube, a screen technology used in televisions and other displays for over 80 years. Picture is produced on a surface at the front of a glass vacuum tube. CRT displays are not flat panel displays and therefore take up more space.', 'CRT stands for Cathode Ray Tube a screen technology used in televisions and other displays for over 80 years Picture is produced on a surface at the front of a glass vacuum tube CRT displays are not flat panel displays and therefore take up more space Benefits As CRT is a much older technology compared to LCD and plasma display panels a high quality CRT screen can be much cheaper than a low range LCD or plasma screen CRT does not exhibit the limited viewing angle or response time delay of LCD panels CRT displays do not have a native resolution like flat panel displays do If they are capable of displaying high definition picture at all they will display it without any downscaling CRT is known to have excellent color and contrast reproduction though LCD panels are fast catching up Drawbacks CRT displays are very heavy and take up a lot of space when compared to flat panel technologies like LCD and plasma display panels CRT displays may deteriorate with age producing less sharp or more unstable picture Magnets or devices which contain magnets or produce a magnetic field should never be placed too close to an operational CRT display as it may cause distortion or in some cases permanent damage Speakers are a common culprit because they contain strong magnets Make sure any speakers are placed at least a foot away from any part of the picture tube unless you are sure that the speakers are magnetically shielded Technical information CRT displays consist of a large glass vacuum tube with electron guns mounted at the rear and colored phosphors covering a panel at the front The electron guns shoot a beam of charged particles through the vacuum toward the phosphors at the front When hitting the phosphors colored light is produced The electron beams are steered left and right over 30 000 times per second and sweeps from top to bottom either 50 or 60 times per second covering the entire screenâ s area 50 or 60 times per second fast enough to give humans the illusion that the entire screen is lit at once The beamâ s intensity is varied as it scans allowing an image to be formed A shadow mask or aperture grille ensures that each beam only hits either the red green or blue phosphors on the screen When lit together these can reproduce all colors CRT technology can also be used in projectors When used in projectors the three color guns red green and blue are usually in three separate vacuum tubes instead of one allowing a greater level of fine detail in smallish tubes The front of each tube has a large lens in front of it focusing the image onto a distant surface like a wall CRT projectors require some rather complication calibration to ensure that all three colors line up properly and the picture on each is perfectly in focus Points of confusion Some CRT displays are advertised as being flat screen This usually means that the front surface of the vacuum tube is flat rather than curved reducing distortion It is not to be confused with a flat panel display like LCD or plasma Sometimes a CRT display advertised as being flat screen still has a curved screen but uses a glass lens at the front whose outer surface is flat to make the display appear flat It is more expensive to produce a CRT display with a true flat front surface for structural reasons the glass tube must withstand the force of the vacuum inside CRT displays rarely accept any type of digital video signal such as DVI or HDMI They are inherently analogue and usually perform at their best with a component video connection Recommendation CRT displays are dropping in popularity due to the emergence of LCD and plasma displays This means it can be hard to find them for sale anymore and unfortunately many of those that are still sold cater to the budget conscious and arenâ t very good screens If you can find a good quality high definition widescreen CRT screen that is not too old you can probably get it at a bargain Otherwise go for an LCD but keep in mind youâ ll be paying much more for an equivalent screen', 'crt,displays,screen,flat,tube,front,display,vacuum,lcd,picture', 1206372924, 1206849667, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
