(428, 382, 1, 'speakers', 'Speakers', 14, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'Speakers, or loudspeakers, produce sound.', 'Speakers or loudspeakers produce sound Form factors Speakers come in many different form factors for different purposes Floorstanding speakers are full length speakers intended to sit flush on the floor They are the tallest speakers available and are intended to reproduce a full range of audio frequencies Unless space is an issue floorstanding speakers are recommended as the main front left and right speakers in any hi fi or home theatre setup Bookshelf speakers are not as tall as floorstanding speakers and are intended to be mounted on stands As is implied by their name they may also be mounted on a shelf Bookshelf speakers reproduce a good range of audio frequencies though their bass response will not usually be as good as floorstanding speakers Bookshelf speakers may be used as main front speakers in a small room or where space is an issue Center speakers are specially designed speakers which are intended to reproduce a â centerâ audio channel in a home theatre setup They are often slim in order to fit neatly above or below a television screen without being too distracting They are also often magnetically shielded so they may be safely placed close to a CRT television and are sold in single units rather than in pairs Center speakers are often very similar in build to equivalent small bookshelf speakers except that they are symmetrical when lying down flat instead of sitting up They can reproduce at least all mid range and high frequency sounds while they do not usually produce much if any bass Bipole speakers are speakers which spread sound in two separate directions instead of directly toward the listener This creates a better illusion of sound â surroundingâ the listener as at least part of the sound heard has been reflected off walls or other objects Bipole speakers are usually used only as surround or rear speakers as they have been specifically designed for this purpose and would be quite unsuitable for main speakers Satellite speakers are very small speakers intended as either main or surround speakers The speaker unit can be as small as a coffee cup or even smaller They only reproduce a very limited range of frequencies and need to be paired with a specially matched woofer to be placed somewhere else in the room Satellite speakers are not recommended in circumstances where audio quality is important their form factor exists mainly for looks rather than function A subwoofer is a large speaker designed to sit on the floor and provide very deep bass sounds Sometimes a subwoofer can contain a built in amplifier requiring it to be plugged in to a power socket This type of subwoofer is called an â activeâ subwoofer Subwoofers are not capable of producing the frequencies heard in speech and thus their use is normally restricted to special effects in movies They may also help to reproduce some of the low frequencies that the main front speakers are not capable of reproducing especially if they are bookshelf or satellite speakers Computer speakers are very small speakers intended to sit on a desk near a computer monitor providing sound for a computer Computer speakers are usuallyvery low quality mounted in plastic They often contain an in built amplifier requiring them to be plugged in to a power socket Headphones are worn on the head for private listening Technical information Almost all speakers consist of one or more drivers Most drivers consist of a cone shaped diaphragm made of a combination of paper cloth and or a synthetic material The cone is rigid and can move forward and backward on its central axis An electromagnet in the back of the cone repels and attracts it to and from a large magnet at the rear of the driver This causes the cone to move When the cone moves forward it compresses the air in front of it and when it moves back it decompresses air These local pressure changes in the air travel as sound waves Drivers of different sizes and shapes are best at producing certain frequencies of sounds As a generalisation the larger a speaker driver the more able it is to produce deeper bass sounds Sound that humans can hear is usually in the range of 20Hz 20 movements of a speaker cone per second and 20 000Hz Most speaker systems can reproduce from around 60 80Hz to 20 000Hz without the aid of a subwoofer Different types of driver are often matched together in the same enclosure in order to cover a wide range of frequencies This is the case in floorstanding bookshelf and center speakers A two way speaker unit contains two different types of drivers whereas a three way speaker unit contains three different types of drivers In each the drivers used to produce the highest treble sounds are called tweeters and the drivers used to produce most lower sounds are called woofers Electronic devices called crossovers are used to separate the incoming audio into high and low frequencies or high mid and low frequencies for two and three way speaker units Points of confusion Speaker units have terminals on the back that accept either bare stranded wire or banana plugs or either Even though it seems to fit either way it is important to hook up your speakers using the correct polarity that is the red terminal on the speaker must connect to the red terminal on the amplifier and the black or uncolored terminal must connect to the black terminal on the amplifier Otherwise your speakers may oppose each other the high pressure part of a cycle on one might coincide with the low pressure part of a cycle on the other cancelling it out and making a â tinnyâ or â lifelessâ sound which varies greatly according to where the listener sits Speaker units quote a maximum power level that they may operate at without distortion This will be measured in Watts RMS a way of measuring power on an alternating current This may lead some people to believe that they should avoid connecting it to an amplifier that puts out more power than this To a large extent the opposite is true It is best to connect an amplifier capable of matching or exceeding the speakersâ maximum power handling without distortion and listen at an appropriate volume The distortion from an underpowered amplifier can cause permanent damage to a speaker even within the speakerâ s maximum power rating Recommendations Your front left and right speakers are the most important in any setup and your front center speaker if you have one If you cannot afford a high quality 5 channel speaker setup it is better to settle for two high quality stereo speakers than five low quality home theatre speakers DVDs blu ray discs and high definition television which uses multiple channels will sound very good coming out of just two speakers if the speakers are good If you have the space and the money get floorstanding front speakers If they are good quality you will be very impressed with them especially for movies Avoid satellite speakers They are sold more for their appearance than their sound quality Their small size made them very fashionable at a time but their low frequency cutoff means that voices and music will suffer requiring the accompanying matched â wooferâ to fill in lower sounds The way you mount your speakers and their location can affect their sound Avoid mounting main front or centre speakers within a few feet from the corner of a room or within a foot or so of a wall The layout of your living room may dictate this somewhat Avoid mounting speakers on top of wooden boards that may cause a rattling sound You can buy special mounting feet â spikesâ at an audio enthusiasts store or you could try damping the rattle using for example and old magazine If you get a subwoofer be very careful to avoid the temptation of setting its level so high that it distorts or it â boomsâ A subwoofer should never be heard on its own its sound should just blend in with the rest of the sound from your system Experiment with lots of different locations to see which sounds best', 'speakers,speaker,sound,frequencies,floorstanding,different,subwoofer,amplifier,reproduce,sounds', 1206372609, 1206375633, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
